00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:32.160
Let's talk about
Android Marshmallow.

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:34.560
As you may know,
Marshmallow introduces

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:36.650
a dynamic permissions
model where

00:03:36.650 --> 00:03:38.810
the app asks the
user for permission

00:03:38.810 --> 00:03:41.715
to do something the first
time it requires it.

00:03:41.715 --> 00:03:45.410
So as a developer, you
need to request permissions

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.940
before your code calls
anything that uses them.

00:03:48.940 --> 00:03:51.500
So it's extra important to
catch connection failures

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:54.450
and initiate a
resolution for failures.

00:03:54.450 --> 00:03:56.720
Should the user
revoke permissions

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:00.330
from Google Play services,
then the resolution user flow

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:01.200
could fix this.

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:04.060
Be sure to check out
the samples for details.

